node.title: 'Very strong chance' COVID has spread into more remote communities as NT records 17 cases overnight
node.description: Seventeen new cases of COVID have recorded in the NT overnight, including 16 linked to the Katherine outbreak, as authorities warn there's a "very strong chance" more remote communities will record cases in coming days.
node.content: ["The Northern Territory\u00a0has recorded 17\u00a0new cases of COVID in the past 24 hours, including 16 local cases.", "Fourteen of the new cases\u00a0are from households in four streets in Katherine East, where a testing blitz had been taking place.", "Of those\u00a014 cases, eight are children under 12, five are aged in their 20s, 30s or 40s, and one is a 70-year-old woman.", "The remaining two cases \u2014 a teenage boy and a man in his 70s \u2014 are already\u00a0in quarantine.", "There was also one positive case from an international repatriation flight.", "\"It's a big number but it's a number that we expected,\" Deputy Chief Minister Nicole\u00a0Manison said.", "\"The blitz is working. We are finding the cases that we thought were there.\"", "She warned that\u00a0authorities were expecting to find more cases.", "Ms Manison flagged that there was a \"very strong chance\" remote communities would record COVID cases in coming days.", "Yesterday authorities announced positive wastewater had been detected in Tennant Creek and five remote communities near Katherine \u2013 Bulla, Daguragu, Pigeonhole, Kalkarindji and Lajamanu.", "Positive cases, Ms Manison said today, would likely require lockout restrictions to be placed on communities where cases were detected.", "\"For the other communities where we have received positive wastewater\u00a0results in the past few days, we are expecting to get a new round of results back at the end of the day,\" she said.", "More to come."]
